Ephemeral volume types, empty dir, host path, and projected.

The first ephemeral type is empty dir, scratch space shared within the pod. It is a brand new empty directory, created when the pod is scheduled and deleted when the pod is removed. There is no persistence. Restarts of the container keep it, but rescheduling the pod to a new node wipes it. By default it is backed by the node's disk, but you can ask for it to be memory backed instead, which is fast and counts against the pod's memory limit. Use empty dir for communication between sidecars, for scratch space isolated per pod, and for buffers that genuinely do not need durability.

The second type is host path, a path on the node mounted into the pod. And here is the warning. Host path is a footgun. It punches a hole through the pod's isolation, exposes the node's internals, makes the pod non portable, and is a security anti pattern. The legitimate uses are narrow. Node level agents, the daemon sets we met earlier, that genuinely need to read host paths, like a log shipper reading the node's logs or a metrics agent reading kernel stats. Cluster bootstrap tooling. And local development on a single node cluster where simplicity matters more than safety. For everything else, including persistence, you reach for persistent volumes instead.

The third group is projected volumes, which combine several sources, like config maps, secrets, and downward ay-pee-eye fields, into a single directory. That is handy when an app expects all of its configuration files together in one place. The common thread across all of these is the same. They live and die with the pod, and none of them survive being rescheduled to another node.
